</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3E3BDF0FD41F4F6" blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3E3BDF0FEB8F49B" bold="true" box="[136,365,1674,1700]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Species richness:—</emphasis>
50 species, of these three occur in 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A19BBDF0FCE1F49B" box="[752,820,1674,1700]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and two in 
<collectingRegion id="DB04F849FF98FFF9A0D2BDF0FB5EF49B" box="[953,1163,1674,1700]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A7F1BDF0FA55F49A" author="Carneiro, A. M. &amp; Farias-Singer, R. &amp; Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D." box="[1178,1408,1674,1701]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" refId="ref8113" refString="Carneiro, A. M., Farias-Singer, R., Ramos, R. A. &amp; Nilson, A. D. (2016) Cactos do Rio Grande do Sul. Fundacao Zoobotanica do Rio Grande do Sul, Porto Alegre, 224 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Carneiro 
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A66EBDF1FAE3F49B" box="[1285,1334,1674,1700]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A6F8BDF1FF32F4F7" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Echinopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oxygona">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A6F8BDF1FF32F4F7" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">E. oxygona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A276BDD5FD5AF4F6" authority="(Oliveira Deble 2011)" baseAuthorityName="Oliveira Deble" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[285,655,1710,1737]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Echinocactus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eyriesii">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A276BDD5FE5BF4F7" box="[285,398,1711,1736]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">E. eyriesii</emphasis>
(Oliveira 
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A169BDD4FD5DF4F6" author="Deble, L. P." box="[514,648,1710,1737]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" pagination="84 - 143" refId="ref8162" refString="Deble, L. P. (2011) A vegetacao campestre no Bioma Pampa. In: Deble, L., Oliveira-Deble, A. S. &amp; Leao, A. L. S. (Eds.) O Bioma Pampa: Contribuicoes cientificas. Ediurcamp, Bage, pp. 84 - 143." type="book chapter" year="2011">Deble 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BDA8FE8DF52E" blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BDA8FE0DF4D3" bold="true" box="[189,472,1746,1772]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">General distribution:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A2B3BDA8FD86F4D3" authorityName="Zuccarini" authorityYear="1837" box="[472,595,1746,1772]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Echinopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A2B3BDA8FD86F4D3" box="[472,595,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Echinopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in southern 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A013BDA8FC6AF4D3" box="[888,959,1746,1772]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A0A1BDA9FBF8F4D2" box="[970,1069,1747,1773]" name="Uruguay" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A752BDA8FB5BF4D3" box="[1081,1166,1746,1772]" name="Bolivia" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A7F2BDA9FAD7F4D2" box="[1177,1282,1747,1773]" name="Paraguay" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="61D7763BFF98FFF9A657BDA8FA7EF4D3" box="[1340,1451,1746,1772]" name="Argentina" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7D514B5AFF98FFF9A3FBBD8DFE99F52E" author="Hunt, D. R. &amp; Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G." box="[144,332,1782,1809]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" refId="ref8565" refString="Hunt, D. R., Taylor, N. P. &amp; Charles, G. (Eds.) (2006) The New Cactus Lexicon. Dh Books, Milborne Port, 373 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Hunt 
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3BBBD8DFEDCF52F" box="[208,265,1782,1808]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="51DA6520FF98FFF9A3D6BC60FBDDF5FB" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BC60FE91F543" blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BC60FD6CF50B" bold="true" box="[189,697,1818,1844]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Distribution in Santa Maria river basin:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF98FFF9A1D2BC60FC4FF50B" box="[697,922,1818,1844]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Echinopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oxygona">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A1D2BC60FC4FF50B" box="[697,922,1818,1844]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Echinopsis oxygona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF98FFF9A0C2BC60FBD4F50A" box="[937,1025,1818,1845]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,609,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-168@7.[302,1286,605,1916]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Cereus hildmaninanus (whitish-pink flowers). B) Echinopsis oxygona (pink flowers). C) Frailea albifusca. D) Frailea castanea. E) Frailea albifusca.F) Frailea lepida.G) Frailea mammifera. H) Frailea pumila. I) Frailea pygmaea.J) Frailea erythracantha K) Gymnocalycium denudatum (white flowers). L) Gymnocalycium uruguayense (yellow flowers). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415611/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), presenting a wide distribution of the study area (
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF98FFF9A262BC44FE9EF566" box="[265,331,1854,1881]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415615/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and in 
<collectingRegion id="DB04F849FF98FFF9A2CDBC44FDACF567" box="[422,633,1854,1880]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
, which may occur mainly in rocky outcrops, native fields associated with saxic vegetation,
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF98FFF9A3D6BCFCFBDDF5FB" blockId="6.[136,1452,1674,1989]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF98FFF9A3D6BCFCFE17F59E" bold="true" box="[189,450,1926,1953]" pageId="6" pageNumber="159">Morphologic notes:—</emphasis>
This species has 8–10 ribs, with flowers. The infusiveness of rose or white-rose petals up to 
<quantity id="DE389B4EFF98FFF9A3CEBCD1FF3FF5FA" box="[165,234,1963,1989]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="159" unit="cm" value="20.0">20 cm</quantity>
long blooms from October to February, bearing fruit shortly thereafter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
